  "diary": "Woke to that grey Seattle drizzle—the kind that makes you want to stay in bed but doesn't actually stop you. Grabbed coffee and wandered over to Belltown Thrift Exchange looking for some vintage band tees. Found a faded Sonic Youth shirt that'll probably end up as flash art someday. Breakfast at Belltown Coffee Co. hit different this morning, maybe because I knew it was going to be a solid day at the studio.\n\nThe SR-520 closure had everyone in a panic, but I'd already mapped out Fremont Ave as my route. Studio was slammed—three back-to-back sessions, one guy getting his first piece, hands shaking a little. There's something about that energy that keeps me sharp. Grabbed a sandwich at Fuel between appointments, barely tasted it. By the time I locked up, the rain had finally stopped and I was running on fumes.\n\nBack home now, ordered Thai food, been messing with chess puzzles on my phone. Feeling that good tired—the kind where your hands remember the work.",
  "thought_process": "The rain and bridge closure could've derailed everything, but I'd already planned around it—sometimes Seattle's chaos just means you have to be a step ahead. I was genuinely excited about the studio work today, especially that first-timer client; that nervous energy is contagious in a good way. Lunch was functional rather than enjoyable, which is typical for busy days. By evening I was mentally checked out but satisfied, so I kept it simple with takeout and low-key leisure. The chess app is my decompression ritual—methodical, quiet, the opposite of tattooing.",
